{{Expand Danish|date=October 2010|Kurantbanken}} The '''Kurantbanken''' (also known as the '''københavnske Assignationsbanken''', '''Vekselbanken''' or '''Laanebankbanken''') was a Danish-Norwegian [[private limited company]] set up in [[Copenhagen]] in 1736, when it received its royal ''oktroj'' or [[royal charter|charter]]. This charter gave it the right to issue banknotes as legal tender for the state (but not for other citizens) - these notes were to be fully convertible (for silver coin).
