{{spanish name|Siale|Bileka}}
'''Silvestre Siale Bileka''' (born 1939?) is an [[Equatorial Guinea|Equato-Guinean]] politician. Bileka served as [[Prime Minister of Equatorial Guinea|Prime Minister]] from 4 March 1992 to 1 April 1996. He is a member of the Partido Democrático de Guinea Ecuatorial ([[Democratic Party of Equatorial Guinea]]).  Bileka also served as President of the Supreme Court, tendering his resignation to [[President of Equatorial Guinea|President]] [[Teodoro Obiang Nguema]] in January 2004.<ref name = "ARB">{{cite journal|year = 2004|title = In Brief|journal = [[Africa Research Bulletin: Political, Social and Cultural Series]]|volume = 41|issue = 1|pages = 15601|doi = 10.1111/j.1467-825X.2004.00195.x}}</ref> The official reason for his resignation was "not being able to reach the desired result in terms of improvement of the operation of the judiciary".<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/pdfid/48a3f02e0.pdf|title = Attacks on Justice – Republic of Equatorial Guinea|publisher = [[United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees|unhcr.org]]|date = May 2005|accessdate = October 29, 2010}}</ref> He was the first senior state official to resign, as the President usually instead simply dismissed his colleagues.<ref name = "ARB" />

