{{Politics of Guinea-Bissau}}

The '''United Platform''' ({{Lang-pt|Plataforma Unida}}, PU) was a political alliance in [[Guinea-Bissau]].

==History==
The PU was established in 2003 as an alliance of the [[Democratic Convergence Party (Guinea-Bissau)|Democratic Convergence Party]], the [[Democratic Front (Guinea-Bissau)|Democratic Front]], the [[Democratic Social Front]], [[Struggle Front for the National Independence of Guinea|FLING]] and the [[Solidarity and Work Party]], and was led by [[Hélder Vaz Lopes]], a former leader of the [[Resistance of Guinea-Bissau-Bafatá Movement]].<ref name=HD>Peter Karibe Mendy (2013) ''Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Guinea-Bissau'', Scarecrow Press, p399</ref> A co-founder was his cousin [[Zinha Vaz]].<ref name="MendyJr.2013">{{cite book|author1=Peter Karibe Mendy|author2=Lobban Jr.|title=Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Guinea-Bissau|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NbJ8AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA394|date=17 October 2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8027-6|pages=394–}}</ref>

The alliance received 4.5% of the vote in the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2004|2004 parliamentary elections]], but failed to win a seat. The PU did not nominate a candidate for the [[Guinea-Bissau presidential election, 2005|2005 presidential elections]], but supported runner-up [[Malam Bacai Sanhá]] of the [[African Party for the Independence of Guinea and Cape Verde|PAIGC]].<ref name=M1>Mendy, p326</ref> The PU was dissolved before the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2008|2008 parliamentary elections]].<ref name=M1/>

